# Cross-Platform Patterns (Allowed Divergence)

**Role Perspective:** Senior Mobile + Web Engineer
**Scope:** When and how platform-specific code is acceptable
**Philosophy:** Maximize code sharing, minimize platform forks, explicit over implicit

---

## Core Principle

> **Default to shared code. Platform-specific behavior must be explicit, minimal, justified, and documented.**

This document clarifies what platform divergence is **allowed** and **expected** while maintaining a single codebase.

---

## 1. What MUST Be Shared (Zero Divergence)

The following **must behave identically** across iOS, Android, and Web:

- ✅ **Business logic** — Data transformations, validation rules, state management
- ✅ **API interactions** — GraphQL queries, mutations, error handling
- ✅ **Data flow** — Props, state updates, data processing
- ✅ **Feature behavior** — What features do, workflows, user journeys
- ✅ **Validation rules** — Form validation, input constraints
- ✅ **Navigation flow** — Screen order, conditional navigation

**Violation of this rule is considered a bug.**

---

## 2. What MAY Differ (Allowed Divergence)

The following **may differ** across platforms when necessary:

### 2.1 Navigation UI Patterns ✅ EXPLICITLY ALLOWED

**Mobile (iOS/Android):**
- Bottom tab navigation
- Stack-based navigation
- Modal presentations
- Swipe gestures

**Web:**
- Top header navigation
- Sidebar navigation
- Breadcrumbs
- Hover-based menus

**Example:**
```typescript
// app/_layout.tsx (Expo Router)
import { Platform } from 'react-native'

export default function RootLayout() {
  if (Platform.OS === 'web') {
    return <WebNavigationLayout />
  }

  return <MobileNavigationLayout />
}
```

**Justification:** Navigation patterns are platform conventions. Users expect different UIs.

---

### 2.2 Layout Density ✅ EXPLICITLY ALLOWED

**Mobile:**
- Single-column layouts
- Full-width components
- Larger touch targets (44x44pt minimum)

**Tablet/Desktop:**
- Multi-column layouts
- Constrained content width
- Denser information display

**Example with NativeWind:**
```tsx
<View className="w-full md:w-1/2 lg:w-1/3">
  {/* Full-width on mobile, narrower on larger screens */}
</View>
```

**Breakpoints (Tailwind/NativeWind):**
- `sm`: 640px
- `md`: 768px
- `lg`: 1024px
- `xl`: 1280px
- `2xl`: 1536px

---

### 2.3 Interaction Patterns ✅ EXPLICITLY ALLOWED

**Touch (Mobile):**
- Tap gestures
- Long-press actions
- Swipe to dismiss

**Mouse/Keyboard (Web):**
- Hover effects
- Click vs. touch
- Keyboard shortcuts
- Focus outlines

**Example:**
```tsx
<Pressable
  className="p-4"
  // Hover effect on web only
  style={({ pressed, hovered }) => ({
    backgroundColor: Platform.OS === 'web' && hovered ? '#f0f0f0' : 'white',
  })}
>
  <Text>Button</Text>
</Pressable>
```

---

### 2.4 Typography Scaling ✅ EXPLICITLY ALLOWED

**Mobile:**
- Larger base font sizes (readability on small screens)
- System font scaling (accessibility)

**Web:**
- Standard web font sizes
- CSS media query scaling

**Example:**
```tsx
<Text className="text-base md:text-sm">
  {/* 16px on mobile, 14px on desktop */}
</Text>
```

---

### 2.5 Safe Area Handling ✅ EXPLICITLY ALLOWED

**iOS:**
- Notch awareness
- Safe area insets

**Android:**
- Status bar overlap
- Navigation bar

**Web:**
- No safe area concerns

**Example:**
```tsx
import { SafeAreaView } from 'react-native-safe-area-context'

// Mobile: Respect safe areas
export function MobileLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return <SafeAreaView edges={['top', 'bottom']}>{children}</SafeAreaView>
}

// Web: No safe areas needed
export function WebLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return <View>{children}</View>
}
```

### 2.6 Dialog & Alert Patterns ✅ EXPLICITLY ALLOWED

**`react-native-web` exports a no-op `Alert.alert()`** — the class is `class Alert { static alert() {} }`. Any `Alert.alert()` call with a buttons array (for confirmation dialogs) silently does nothing on web: callbacks never fire, no dialog appears.

**Solution:** Use a cross-platform wrapper utility instead of `Alert.alert()` directly:

```typescript
// src/shared/utils/alert.ts
import { Alert, Platform } from 'react-native'

export function showAlert(title: string, message?: string, buttons?: AlertButton[]) {
  if (Platform.OS !== 'web') {
    Alert.alert(title, message, buttons)
    return
  }
  const fullMessage = message ? `${title}\n\n${message}` : title
  if (!buttons || buttons.length <= 1) {
    window.alert(fullMessage)
    buttons?.[0]?.onPress?.()
    return
  }
  // Multi-button: use window.confirm()
  const cancelButton = buttons.find((b) => b.style === 'cancel')
  const actionButton = buttons.find((b) => b.style !== 'cancel') ?? buttons[buttons.length - 1]
  const confirmed = window.confirm(fullMessage)
  if (confirmed) actionButton?.onPress?.()
  else cancelButton?.onPress?.()
}
```

**Rule:** Never use `Alert.alert()` directly in screens or components. Always use `showAlert()` from the shared utility.

